07008nam a22010335i 9783110616415DE-B159720210421021438.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210421t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020945771  a97831106164157 a10.1515/97831106164152doi  a(DE-B1597)527155  a(OCoLC)1233041757  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0220002bisacsh0485pa709.2qDE-10100aVisual Antisemitism in Central Europe :bImagery of Hatred /cJakub Hauser, Eva Janáčová. 1aMünchen ;aWien : bDe Gruyter Oldenbourg, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (X, 290 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tIntroduction -- tThe Metamorphoses of the Judensau -- tImagining Ritual Murder: Social Knowledge in the Making -- tSpa Antisemitism in Bohemia and Moravia -- tJews Out of Place? Place and Space in Czech Antisemitic Caricatures -- tSimple Entertainment? Die Muskete and 'Weak' Antisemitism in Interwar Vienna -- tFaithful to Tradition: Visual Depictions of Antisemitism in Humoristické listy in the 1920s and 1930s -- tAntisemitic Caricatures in the Protectorate Press (1939-1945) and their Authors -- tPolish Jews in the Visual Reporting of the Propaganda Companies -- tVisual Depictions of Antisemitism in the Czech Lands after World War II -- tContemporary Visual Antisemitism in the Czech Republic -- tRefugees 'as Jews'. Travelling Images of Atrocities -- tIndex of Names -- tList of Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn eleven contributions, Visual Antisemitism in Central Europe, Imagery of Hatred deals with visual manifestations of antisemitism in Central Europe from the Middle Ages to the present day. The publication, which presents heretofore largely unknown materials, seeks responses from diverse perspectives to the question of the role of visuality in the development of antisemitic moods and political agendas that encouraged hatred towards Jews. The scope of visual anti-Judaism and antisemitism always was and still is very wide: from stereotypical depictions that can conceal an underlying message through humorous content, to clearly formulated assaults that aim to escalate animosity towards an imaginary collective enemy. The goal in both these cases is the exclusion of Jews from the majority society imagined as a monolithic whole, and the reification of a dividing line between "us" and "them". With its wide thematic and methodological range, this book offers a comprehensive image of the phenomenon of visual anti-Judaism and antisemitism and provides rich comparative material for the entire Central European region.  aIn what way has anti-Semitism influenced fine art and visual culture in Central Europe from the Middle Ages to the present day? Is there an embedded anti-Semitic iconography? Why does visual antisemitism arise today? The volume will deal also with questions of how to write about the visual history of anti-Semitism and exhibit anti-Semitic works to the public without contributing to the support of hate movements.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 4aKunst. 4aMitteleuropa. 4aVisueller Antisemitismus. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aArts and Visual Culture.  aCentral Europe.  aVisual anti-Semitism.1 aDienstbier, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrankl, Michal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHauser, Jakub, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHauser, Jakub, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJanáčová, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanáčová, Eva, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKarlíček,